equation_narrative.headline: C-terminal position context drives threonine prediction through polar-specific features
equation_narrative.story: Position 66 is the penultimate residue in ubiquitin's C-terminal tail (sequence ...IQKES[T]LHLVL...), a critical region for ubiquitin recognition. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation reflecting this terminal context: local sequence features dominate early attention (L8 head 6 writes +4.1 to answer), while structural contacts from 5 nearby residues provide modest input. The logit lens shows volatile early character—serine leads initially (22.6% at L0), followed by transient shifts through histidine, tyrosine, glycine, and various hydrophobic residues—but this reflects the model encoding diverse contextual features, not prediction uncertainty. The decision crystallizes at L24-26: threonine-specific prediction channels activate (F30:5918, F30:2675 with ~20 proj each), MLP neurons in L28-32 cast strong votes for T (N28:3284 at +0.96, N30:620 at +0.97), and threonine surges from 22% at L23 to 99% by L33, overwhelming brief competition from valine.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a representation of the C-terminal context through primarily local sequence reading. L8 head 6 delivers the strongest early signal (+4.1 proj, 76.8% local attention), establishing position-in-sequence encoding. Structural contacts contribute modestly (5 residues within 8Å) with only 2 co-evolving positions detected, indicating this terminal position is more constrained by local sequence than by 3D packing or evolutionary coupling. The logit lens shows 14 lead changes through L23—S→H→Y→G→N→L→A→K→L→V→K→V→T—reflecting the model's progressive refinement of abstract features rather than prediction instability. Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 at ~45 proj) encode positional context, while mid-layer features (F9:5728 at 54.8, F18:9820 at 19.6) capture secondary structure and terminal-position characteristics. By L23, the representation stabilizes with T at 22%, V at 21%, and I at 15%, consistent with small polar or hydrophobic residues appropriate for a flexible C-terminal tail.
perception_phase.context_character: C-terminal tail position with strong local sequence constraints and weak structural packing. The context favors small, flexible residues (polar or hydrophobic) suitable for a solvent-exposed terminal region with minimal evolutionary coupling.
key_information_sources: Local sequence dominance: L8 head 6 writes +4.1 (76.8% local attention), encoding C-terminal position context
Structural contacts: 5 residues within 8Å, providing modest 3D environment signal
Minimal co-evolution: only 2 coupled positions detected, indicating local sequence primacy
Terminal position encoding: F9:5728 (54.8 proj), F18:9820 (19.6 proj) capture C-terminal tail characteristics

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase (L24-33) activates threonine-specific prediction machinery. At L24, valine briefly peaks (25.3%) as the representation tests hydrophobic alternatives, but L26 marks the decisive shift: T overtakes V (32.3% vs 24.5%) as polar-specific features engage. MLP neurons in L28-32 deliver the strongest votes: N28:3284 projects +0.96 to T, N30:620 adds +0.97, and N31:4008 contributes +0.86. Layer 30 SAE features (F30:5918, F30:2675, F30:8249 all ~20 proj) encode threonine-specific prediction channels. The final layers (L31-33) consolidate this decision through massive MLP support (L31 total +16.45, L29 total +4.49), driving T from 53% at L29 to 99% at L33.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the perception-to-decision shift. At L23, the representation remains multi-modal (T 22%, V 21%, I 15%) with no clear commitment. L24 briefly tests valine (peaks at 25.3%), but L25-26 activates amino-acid-specific prediction features: F24:10131 (20.2 proj) and F24:7582 (18.7 proj) emerge as early decision channels, and MLP L25 delivers +1.45 net support for T. By L26, threonine-specific neurons dominate (N26:833 at +0.54) and T establishes a lead it never relinquishes.

candidates.narrative: Threonine emerges as the clear winner through L24-33 via strong MLP support and polar-specific prediction channels. After hovering at 8-22% through L23, T surges at L26 (32.3%) when polar-specific features activate. The decisive push comes from L28-32 MLP neurons: N28:3284 (+0.96 proj, top vote for T), N30:620 (+0.97), N30:3886 (+0.81), and N31:4008 (+0.86) collectively drive T from 53% at L29 to 99% at L33. Layer 30 SAE features (F30:5918, F30:2675, F30:8249 all ~20 proj) encode threonine-specific prediction channels that consolidate the decision.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges decisively at L26, dominant by L30, reaches 98.8% by L33
key_evidence: N28:3284 (MLP, +0.96 proj) — strongest single T vote, also supports M and K
N30:620 (+0.97 proj) — top vote for K but strong T support
F30:5918, F30:2675, F30:8249 (all ~20 proj) — threonine-specific prediction channels
L29-31 MLP layers deliver +4.49, +6.04, +16.45 total support respectively

candidates.narrative: Valine briefly challenges threonine at the decision boundary, peaking at 25.3% at L24 before collapsing. This transient surge reflects the model testing hydrophobic alternatives appropriate for the C-terminal tail context. V rises from 12% at L0 to 21% at L23, then spikes to 25.3% at L24 as the representation transitions from perception to decision. However, L26-28 MLP neurons actively suppress V: N26:2816 erases -0.54 (top vote for I at +0.68), N28:5072 erases -0.52 (top vote for V at +0.46), driving V down to 6.4% by L29 and 0.23% finally.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L24 (25.3%), collapses by L29 (6.4%)

N26:2816 (MLP, -0.54 proj) — erases V, votes for I instead
N28:5072 (-0.52 proj) — suppresses V despite V being its top vote
Loses decisively to T at L26 (24.5% vs 32.3%)

candidates.narrative: Serine leads the logit lens at L0 (22.6%) because the embedding representation is initially consistent with small polar residues—S and T are chemically similar and both appropriate for C-terminal positions. This is not a model prediction but rather reflects that the initial embedding, before any contextual processing, correlates with polar character. S declines through early layers (5.5% at L8) as the model reads local sequence context, briefly recovers to 11% at L17 and L29 as polar features resurface, but ultimately collapses to 0.34% as threonine-specific channels dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Leads at L0 (22.6%), fades by L8 (5.5%), eliminated by L33 (0.34%)
key_evidence: L0 embedding: 22.6% reflects initial polar character before context processing
Chemically similar to T (both small polar) but lacks T-specific support
Brief recovery at L29 (11.05%) as polar features activate, but T-specific neurons prevail

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine emerges as a late-perception contender, rising from 1.2% at L0 to 15.3% at L23 as the model encodes hydrophobic alternatives for the C-terminal tail. This trajectory reflects the representation becoming consistent with buried hydrophobic residues during mid-layer structural feature assembly. However, I peaks at L23 and collapses immediately in the decision phase (2.1% by L29) as polar-specific prediction channels activate and MLP neurons suppress hydrophobic candidates.
candidates.key_layers: Rises through L1-23 (1.2% → 15.3%), peaks at L23, collapses by L29 (2.1%)
key_evidence: L17-23: steady rise from 3.7% to 15.3% as hydrophobic representation builds
Peak at L23 (15.3%) marks end of perception phase

candidates.narrative: Alanine peaks early at L12 (21.7%) when the logit lens representation is consistent with small hydrophobic residues, reflecting the model's encoding of C-terminal flexibility constraints. This is not a prediction but rather indicates the mid-layer representation correlates with alanine-like features (small, hydrophobic, helix-compatible). A declines steadily after L12 as polar features accumulate, dropping to 2.9% by L23 and 0.36% finally as threonine-specific decision channels activate.

turning_points.description: Early context assembly establishes C-terminal position encoding. L8 head 6 delivers the strongest perception-phase signal (+4.1 proj, 76.8% local attention), reading the immediate sequence context (...IQKES[T]LHLVL...). This triggers volatile logit-lens shifts (G→N→L→A) as the model encodes diverse positional features, not prediction uncertainty. L10 attention adds +7.35 toward T while L10 MLP erases -3.86, reflecting the model's simultaneous encoding of polar potential and hydrophobic alternatives.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation remains multi-modal (T 22%, V 21%, I 15%) with no commitment. L24 briefly tests valine (25.3% peak) as the model evaluates hydrophobic alternatives. L25-26 activates amino-acid-specific prediction machinery: F24:10131 and F24:7582 (~19 proj each) emerge as early decision channels, L25 MLP delivers +1.45 net T support (N25:855 at +0.61), and L26 MLP adds +1.79 (N26:833 at +0.54). T overtakes V decisively at L26 (32.3% vs 24.5%), establishing a lead that accelerates through final layers.

Final decision consolidation through massive MLP support. L29 delivers +4.49 total (N29:4973 at +0.87, N29:873 at +0.66), L30 adds +6.04 (N30:620 at +0.97, N30:3886 at +0.81), L31 contributes +16.45 (N31:4008 at +0.86, N31:1061 at +0.78), and L32 adds +16.57 via MLP (N32:516 at +1.31). These layers activate threonine-specific prediction channels (F30:5918, F30:2675, F30:8249 all ~20 proj) while suppressing alternatives: N30:2809 erases -0.62 (votes for L/R), N31:3784 erases -0.87 (votes for Y/R). T surges from 52.9% at L29 to 98.8% at L33.

These neurons cast strong threonine-specific votes while suppressing hydrophobic and charged alternatives.

deep_dives.caption: The final acceleration: L30 MLP +4.58, L31 MLP +6.12, L32 MLP +16.57 drive T from 52.9% to 98.8%. L33 attention delivers -19.51 (erasing alternatives) while L33 MLP is silent, indicating the decision is complete and final layer attention performs cleanup.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts threonine by assembling a C-terminal position context through local sequence reading (L8 head 6, +4.1 proj) and recognizing this as the penultimate residue in ubiquitin's flexible tail. The perception phase (L1-23) encodes positional constraints through volatile logit-lens shifts that reflect feature assembly, not prediction uncertainty. The decision crystallizes at L24-26 when polar-specific prediction channels activate (F24:10131, F24:7582), and MLP neurons in L28-32 deliver overwhelming threonine support (N28:3284, N30:620, N31:4008 collectively +2.6 proj). The strongest evidence is the massive L29-32 MLP consolidation (+27 total proj) that drives T from 53% to 99%, suppressing all alternatives including the briefly competitive valine. The model's confidence (98.8%) reflects the unambiguous C-terminal context and strong threonine-specific feature activation in late layers.
